Author: jl777c#5810
Content: on the computer

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: though in the beginning I had to use paper and pencil to draw out how things connected to each other, but over the years I found it much faster just to write the code directly

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: i mostly now just copy and paste working methods from the past and just morph it a bit

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: well, when I say copy, I mean recall how I solved a similar problem, and write the customized code for the current problem at hand. no need to waste time looking through millions of lines of old code

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: the hard part is to simplify a bigger problem into two or more simpler problems. keep doing that until one of the problems is similar to something you solved before. morph a solution for that and the entire problem is now one simple sub-problem simpler. keep doing that until there are no problems left.

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: seems to work effectively in most all cases

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: but sometimes, i need to take a step back and just refactor the entire thing, if it evolved into too messy of a thing to be easy to maintain
